5. CV Binary Routing Through Simulation

Why GCTA must use the CV binary
Causal variants are sampled from CV_TO_SIMS.bim by PYTHON_SIMULATE_EFFECTS_GLOBAL. These variants may not be in TO_SIMS.bim (the marker SNP set) if cv_maf &lt; ms_maf or if LD pruning removed them from the marker set. Because GCTA’s --simu-qt requires the causal variants to be present in the input --bfile, phenotype simulation must use the CV binary (--bfile CV_TO_SIMS), not the marker set binary.


.tap{} fix for three-subscriber queue channel
ch_sf.marker_set_params is a Nextflow queue channel emitting one item per strain group. In DSL2, queue channels are consumed once — if three downstream processes each try to read from the same channel, emissions are distributed round-robin instead of broadcast. The fix uses .tap{} to clone the channel before any subscriber reads it:
// ch_sf.marker_set_params is a queue channel — fan out with .tap{} before
// 3 subscribers consume it (write_marker_set, write_genotype_matrix, write_gwa_to_db).
// Without this, DSL2 distributes emissions round-robin among competing readers.
ch_sf.marker_set_params
    .tap { ch_marker_set_params_for_ms }
    .tap { ch_marker_set_params_for_gm }
    .set { ch_marker_set_params_for_gwa }
Each of the three DB-write processes receives a complete, independent copy of the marker-set parameter tuples.
